Levi's theorem says that a finite-dimensional Lie algebra is a semidirect product of its radical and the complementary subalgebra (Levi subalgebra).

A "derivation" on the Lie algebra formula_14 (or on any non-associative algebra) is a linear map formula_63 that obeys the Leibniz law, that is,

for all formula_37. The "inner derivation" associated to any formula_66 is the adjoint mapping formula_67 defined by formula_68. (This is a derivation as a consequence of the Jacobi identity.) If formula_14 is semisimple, every derivation is inner.

The derivations form a vector space formula_70, which is a Lie algebra under the commutator bracket formula_71, where formula_72denotes composition of mappings. The inner derivations form a Lie subalgebra of formula_70.

Let "V" be a finite-dimensional vector space over a field "F", formula_74 the Lie algebra of linear transformations and formula_75 a Lie subalgebra. Then formula_14 is said to be split if the roots of the characteristic polynomials of all linear transformations in formula_14 are in the base field "F". More generally, a finite-dimensional Lie algebra formula_14 is said to be split if it has a Cartan subalgebra whose image under the adjoint representation formula_79 is a split Lie algebra. A split form of a complex semisimple Lie algebra (cf. #Real form and complexification) is an example. See also split Lie algebra for further information.

Any vector space formula_80 endowed with the identically zero Lie bracket becomes a Lie algebra. Such Lie algebras are called abelian, cf. below. Any one-dimensional Lie algebra over a field is abelian, by the alternating property of the Lie bracket.

