A complex matrix group is a Lie group consisting of matrices, formula_98, where the multiplication of "G" is matrix multiplication. The corresponding Lie algebra formula_1 is the space of matrices which are tangent vectors to "G" inside the linear space formula_100: this consists of derivatives of smooth curves in "G" at the identity: formula_101The Lie bracket of formula_14 is given by the commutator of matrices, formula_103. Given the Lie algebra, one can recover the Lie group as the image of the matrix exponential mapping formula_104 defined by formula_105, which converges for every matrix formula_106: that is, formula_107. 
